 In Strict Confidence \"Promised Land\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix) on In Strict Confidence \"The Serpent's Kiss\" (Minuswelt Musikfabrik)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/In-Strict-Confidence-The-Serpents-Kiss/release/820201|title=In Strict Confidence \u2013 The Serpent's Kiss|publisher=discogs.com|accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n* 2000 Digital 21 \"Anymore\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n* 1997 In The Dark \"Number One\" (Maydr\u00efm Remix)\n\n===Featured songs===\n\n* 2008 Luis Ramiro \"Estrella\" on \"Estrella\" film soundtrack\n* 2008 Marwan \u201cEl Pr\u00f3ximo Verano\" on Marwan \u201cTrapecista\u201d album\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Monica Castell \"Killing Moon\" on Various Artistes \"Play the Game: Tributo a Echo and the Bunnymen\" (Lunar Records)\n* 2005 Maydr\u00efm featuring Carita Boronska \"Shakespeare's Sister\" on Various Artistes \"Una luz que nunca se apagar\u00e1: Tributo a The Smiths\" (El Diablo)\n\n===Session recordings===\n\n* 2011 Amaral \"Hacia Lo Salvaje\" album (Ant\u00e1rtida)\n* 2010 La Mari (Chambao) on Ni\u00f1o Raro \u201cTreinta y Tres\u201d album\n* 2009 OBK \"Tal Vez\" [Antipop Version]\n* 2009 Zahara on Lucas \"Palo Al Agua\" album (EMI Espa\u00f1a)\n* 2005 Danny Reus & The Gospel Factory on Lonely Joe \u201cSongs From The Low Side\u201d album (Subterfuge Records)\n* 2002-4 Carita Boronska, advertising campaigns\n* 2001 Naymi, debut album (Sony Music Media)\n* 2001 Carles Benavent on Jos\u00e9 Ortega \"La Rosa De Tu Piel\" album\n\n==See also==\n* [[Superbrands]]\n* [[:es:Rock espanol|Rock Espa\u00f1ol]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.antipop.es Antonio Escobar}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100823104243/http://www.maydrim.com/ Maydr\u00efm Maydrim Official Site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Escobar Nunez, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pamplona]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Madrid]]\n[[Category:Andalusian musicians]]\n[[Category:Rock en Espa\u00f1ol musicians]]\n[[Category:Spanish composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish male composers]]\n[[Category:Spanish film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:People of Andalusian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Escobar_N%C3%BA%C3%B1ez"}
{"title_page": "Po\u00e9sie Noire", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Po\u00e9sie Noire\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Belgium]]\n| genre               = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[dark wave]], [[synthpop]], [[Synthpop|electropop]], [[gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = 1984&ndash;1992\n| label               = [[ARS Records]]<br/>[[Antler-Subway]]<br/>[[EMI]] Belgium<br/>Stiletto<br/>[[Boy Records (Spain)]]\n| associated_acts     = [[TBX]]\n| current_members     = [[Johan Casters]]<br>[[Marianne Valvekens]]<br>[[Herman Gillis]]<br>[[Evanna]]<br>[[Ludo Camberlin aka Carl S. Johansen]] (the [[TBX]] project.)\n}}\n\n'''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' are a [[Belgium|Belgian]] band that rose to prominence in the mid-'80s. Their [[Belgium|Belgian]] origins and tendency to develop a goth-oriented, synthetic, gloomy universe with low-pitched voices - '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' could translate by ''\"Black/Dark Poetry\"'' - had them categorized as [[Electronic body music|EBM]] such as other [[Belgium|Belgian]] members of the 1980s [[electronic music]] scene like [[\u00c0;GRUMH...]] or [[A Split-Second]]. However, much in the manner of various renowned [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Electronic body music|EBM]] bands like [[The Neon Judgement]] and, to some extent, [[Front 242]], they declared, through their music,\na will to step away from the usual [[industrial music|industrial]] aggressiveness that characterized [[Electronic body music]] and developed a more [[mainstream]] accessible dark pop sound that helped them to be regarded as plain [[New wave music|new wave]] or [[Darkwave]].<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/articles/div-GermanArticle/index.html Translation of a German article about the band's influences]</ref><ref>[http://www.lastfm.fr/music/+noredirect/poesie+noire Po\u00e9sie Noire short review at last.fm]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Band Members===\n\nInitially based on seven members, Po\u00e9sie Noire rapidly boiled down to just three hardcore members so as to be finally incarnated by [[Johan Casters]] aka ''\"La B\u00eate Noire\"'' - ''\"The Black/Dark Beast\"'' - (writer, composer and main male singer of the band),  [[Marianne Valvekens]] (co-writer, female vocalist up to the 1991 '''''Marianne''''' album  - and then back on '''''Sense Of Purpose''''' - and keyboard player) and [[Herman Gillis]] (co-writer and mainly the band's guitar player.) As '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' 's fanbase grew along the years, [[Johan Casters|Johan]] and [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] were soon to be given ''\"status nicknames\"'' (probably in tradition of some typically ''\"Goth-spirited\"'' symbolical hierarchy.) Consequently, it did not take long for [[Johan Casters|Casters]] to be considered the band's ''\"Master\"'' to the fans whereas [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] became their ''\"Goddess\"''.\n\nIn 1991, Irish vocalist [[Evanna]] joined the band for the '''''Marianne''''' album because producer [[Ludo Camberlin]] didn't feel [[Marianne Valverken|Marianne]]'s voice was right for the album and [[Evanna]]'s had more warmth and soul to it.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/faq/index.html Marianne and Jo answer to FAQ's]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref>\n\n===Career summary===\n\nVery little is known about how the band actually started their career in music. Nevertheless, they are known to have won the 1985 Breekend Rock Festival (a long-lasting, reputed festival set in [[Bree, Belgium]] that hosted large amounts of prestigious bands such as [[The Smiths]] in 1984 or even [[Slade]] in 2009<ref>[http://www.setlist.fm/venue/breekend-festival-bree-belgium-13d60da1.html The Smiths and Slade at Breekend Festival]</ref>) This domestic victory probably played a part in giving the band a flattering reputation because the following year, Po\u00e9sie Noire started supporting [[Dead Can Dance]]<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/giglist/19860521/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire supporting Dead Can Dance]</ref>\nand [[The Sisters of Mercy]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} on tour, seizing this great opportunity of getting in touch with those huge [[post-punk]], [[goth rock]] bands' audiences to display their own musical conception of darkness to them and have personal gigs set up in the meantime.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's Official Site : Introduction]</ref>\nAlong their years as Po\u00e9sie Noire, the band demonstrated qualities as a prolific act with intensive releases : in just seven years, [[Johan Casters|Casters]], [[Marianne Valvekens|Valvekens]] and [[Herman Gillis|Gillis]] offered their fans 9 albums and mini-albums, 2 official ''best of compilation'', 1 remix compilation and 15 singles which allowed them to appear on various [[Electronic body music|EBM]] or [[New wave music|new wave]] compilations and become genuine figures of the kind throughout their sphere of influence.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=A Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Albums and Mini Albums Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=S Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Singles Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/compilations/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Compilations Section]</ref>\n\n===TBX===\n\nBy 1992, it seems the relations between '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' and their label, Antler-Subway, were not as sound as they used to. Indeed, the record label promised the band they would release yet another album of the band's composition entitled '''''Delirious''''' but this never happened and Antler-Subway finally released [[Johan Casters|Jo]], [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] and newcomer [[Evanna]] from their recording contract instead.\n\nWith the help of [[Ludo Camberlin]] aka Carl S. Johansen, who had been their producer since the 1989 album '''''Love is Colder than Death''''',<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref> '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' changed their name to [[TBX]] (''\"To Be eXcited\"'', that is) and signed to larger label [[EMI]] Belgium that enabled them to release this '''''Delirious''''' album which had been the source of so many issues and changes. But unfortunately for the band, this ''\"new beginning\"'' rapidly ended up unsuccessful - because the band's ''\"music [was not] meant for [the] mass consumption [that ''[[EMI]]'' was used to aiming at]\"'', their official site explains  - and led [[EMI]] Belgium to delete [[TBX]] from their catalog promptly afterwards.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's Official Site : Introduction]</ref> Consequently, for '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''', the bell tolled although they finally returned in 2010 with a new album, '''''Sense Of Purpose'''''.\n\n===Sense Of Purpose===\n\nMore than a decade after the band split, they formed again and started working on a new album, '''''Sense Of Purpose''''',<ref>[http://www.e-musique.com/music/poesie-noire-sense-of-purpose/ e-musique's article about the release of \"Sense of Purpose\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210143634/http://www.e-musique.com/music/poesie-noire-sense-of-purpose/ |date=2010-12-10 }}</ref> finally released in October 2010 under the name that made them famous, '''Po\u00e9sie Noire'''.\n\nThe release of this new opus went along with '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' taking part in the Sinner's Day festival,<ref>[http://www.sinnersday.com/content/line-up Line-up of Sinner's Day festival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907163328/http://www.sinnersday.com/content/line-up |date=2010-09-07 }}</ref> on October 31, 2010, together with such prestigious artists as [[Heaven 17]], [[Nina Hagen]], [[Marc Almond]], [[The Psychedelic Furs]], [[Echo & the Bunnymen]], [[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]], [[The Selecter]], [[Department S (TV series)|Department S]], [[Marky Ramone]], [[Jah Wobble]] or [[Young Gods]].\n\n==Side-Projects and Aftermath==\n\nAfter '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' disbanded, their members carried on musical projects they had been involved in while the band was active, developed new ones or radically turned over a new leaf.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/sideprojects/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Side Projects]</ref>\n\n===Johan Casters===\n\nUsing different aliases (Morton, Joey Morton, Pateke Morton, Ilya Dimitrijevic,Jill (or Jille) Johnson or Alessandro Di Ravo), [[Johan Casters]] has extensively served as a writer, producer and even remixer or editor for various acts and artists. He has developed personal projects from the late 1980s onwards, either alone or with [[Herman Gillis]].\n\nAs a producer or executive producer, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] has been involved in several obscure projects such as [[The Passion of a Primitif]], [[Company of State]], [[Men 2nd]], [[In Sotto Voce]], [[Attrition (band)|Attrition]], [[Ei Mori]], [[Bulgarka]], [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]], [[Pussy Jew]], [[Dee Bass]], [[Translator (music)|Translator]], [[Minimalistix]], [[Orion Too feat. Caitlin]], [[Roxane (music)|Roxane]] and [[Biba Binoche]].\n\nAs a remixer or editor, once again, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] has linked up with a large selection of artists from very obscure to popular favourites as proved by the following list : [[The Neon Judgement]], [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]], [[The Weathermen (Belgian band)|The Weathermen]], [[Jean-Jacques Smoothie]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]].\n\nThough [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] seem to go on making music together, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] was known, in the late 1990s, to be working in the field of important musical events coordination and then as [[A&R]] for the Roadrunner turned Mostiko<ref>[http://www.mostiko.be/ Mostiko]</ref>  division of [[Arcade/CNR]].\n\n===Johan Casters and Herman Gillis (and sometimes, Marianne)===\n\nWhile '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' was still active, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] have been involved as writers and composers in the full or partial development of original or pre-existing projects (with the occasional help of [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]]). The two of them usually worked together though, every once in a while, only one of them would be involved. The massive list of projects the two happen to be behind includes [[In Sotto Voce]], [[Brothers on Acid]], [[Ei Mori]], [[Bulgarka]], [[Trio Balkana]], [[Fruit of Life (music)|Fruit of Life]], [[Erotic Dissidents]], [[Mission Impossible (music)|Mission Impossible]], [[The Brothers (music)|The Brothers]], [[Morton, Sherman and Bellucci]], [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]], [[Opium Monks]], [[Berliner Meisterschaft]], [[The Secrets of China]], [[Kings of Agreppo]], [[Explorers of the Nile]], [[Taste of Sugar feat. K. Finley]], [[TNT Clan]], [[The New Beat Sensation]], [[Msb Sound System]], [[Beat Professor]], [[The Freak Brothers]], [[Student Fashion]], [[Mr. Horse (music)|Mr. Horse]], [[Subway's new Acid House Techno Beat]], [[Balearic Beach]], [[M.S.B.]], [[Supernova (music)|Supernova]], [[Brotherhood of Sleep]], [[The Moneymakers]], [[The Airplane Crashers]], [[Voor Den Broode]], [[German Beat Syndrome]], [[Neue Beat Collectione]], [[Matt's Phantasy Club]], [[Serious ft.JJ Maurie]],  [[Boris Mikulic]], [[J.E.T.]], [[Strictly Nervous]].\n\n===Herman Gillis===\n\nSimilarly to [[Johan Casters|Casters]], while he was already busy co-writing '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' tracks and playing the guitar on them, [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] made sure to develop parallel activities as a producer, writer, composer, programmer and musician using, like his fellow singer, multiple nicknames : Sherman, Herman Sherman, Boris Mikulic and Tessa Rossa. Those activities can be traced back to 1987 until 1994.\n\nAmong the projects he worked for as a writer or co-writer, one should note that he regularly assumed the position of a musician in some of them and took care of programming, keyboards and guitar-playing. Included in this category are [[The Passion of a Primitif]] (1987), [[Company of State]] (1987; 1988), [[In Sotto Voce]] - actually, a genuine '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' side-project posing as a Yugoslavian act. It was incarnated by [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Herman Gillis|Herman]], respectively pretending to be Ilya Dimitrijevic and Boris Mikulic. The point of creating those bogus identities and launching this project was to give a ''\"response to a belgian journalist who found Po\u00e9sie Noire too \"poppy\" \"'' (the official site claims)  - (1987; 1988; 1989), [[Boris Mikulic]] (1990), [[Volt (music)|Volt]] (formerly known as [[Running Cow]]) (1993)...\n\n[[Herman Gillis|Gillis]], much like [[Johan Casters|Casters]], also remixed or edited recordings by various artists either with or without [[Johan Casters|Jo]] : [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]] (1989), [[Take 6 (music)|Take 6]] and [[Take 7]] (19??), [[DWF (music)|DWF]] (1990), [[Wire (band)|Wire]]...\n\nProducing records soon got [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] interested and he quickly had his own production company set up : [[Sherman Productions]]. Among the acts produced by him - either with or without [[Johan Casters|Jo]], once again - one can point out : [[Ei Mori]] (1988), [[Bulgarka]] (1988), [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]] (1988), [[Boris Mikulic]] (1990), [[Spectralyzer]] (1991), [[Trance Too]] (1991), [[Volt (music)|Volt]] (1993-1994) or [[Hypnotyz]] (199?).\n\n[[Herman Gillis]] is also reputed for working on a first hand-made filter known as the [[Sherman Filterbank]]<ref>[http://www.sherman.be/ Sherman Filterbank website]</ref> used by many renowned artists such as [[Air (French band)|Air]], [[The Chemical Brothers]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] or [[The Rolling Stones]].<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/Herman/index.html Herman Gillis]</ref> After the band [[Volt (music)|Volt]] he was involved in split up, [[Herman Gillis|Gillis]] decided he would resign from the music scene and dedicate his energy to the conception of electronic filters and effect boxes of the same kind.\n\n===Marianne Valvekens===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/faq/index.html Marianne and Jo answer to FAQ's]</ref>\n\nContrarily to Jo and Hermann, it seems that record production was never an ambition to Marianne which did not stop her from lending her voice to other '''Po\u00e9sie Noire'''-related projects - being sometimes credited as [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne ''\"the Ice Queen\"'' Valvekens]] - and taking part in the writing and composing of other projects, as well.\n\nAs a vocalist, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]], along with [[Johan Casters|Jo]], took part in the 1986 '''''Mijn-Alarm''''' (''\"Mine-Alarm\"'' in Dutch) project which consisted in gathering the singers from 19 Belgian bands such as [[The Scabs]], [[The Pop Gun]] or [[Siglo XX (band)|Siglo XX]]: each of them were to sing a couple lines from the project's song so as to produce a record whose goal was to raise money for the [[Limburg, Belgium|Limburg]] mineworkers. Later, in 2001, she also gave her voice to [[M&M Project feat.M]]'s ''''''Wide anthem (Sometimes It Hurt)''''' - the final '\"M\"' stood for [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] - one of the many [[Johan Casters|Johan]]-related projects she contributed to also as a writer-composer.\n\nWhen she assumed those positions, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] used two pseudonyms - Laura Furia and Mateke Porton - which she signed several contributions to various projects with : '''''Strictly Nervous, A Collection Of Acid Jazz - Jazzy House - Jazz Dance''''' (1993), [[M&M Project feat.M]]'s ''''''Wide anthem (Sometimes It Hurt)''''' (2001), [[Orion Too feat.Caitlin]]'s '''''Hope and Wait''''' (2002), '''''So Shy''''' (2002),'''''Travelling''''' (2003) and '''''Making Love For The First Time''''' (2003), [[Biba Binoche]]'s '''''Je Chante pour toi''''' (2004) and [[X3 vs Francis Goya]]'s '''''Rain, the guitar song''''' (2003).\n\nAround 2003, she was also said to be writing a book but no further piece of news has ever surfaced about it since then.\n\nHowever, it seems that from the late 1990s onwards, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]]'s main occupation has been as a worker in some kind of employment agency.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's official site introduction]</ref>\n\n===Evanna===\n\nAfter her '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''' years, it seems [[Evanna]] has not been heard of again in the music-making business\n\n===Ludo Camberlin/Carl S. Johansen===\n\nWhile living the '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''' episode, [[Ludo Camberlin]] also worked as a producer on projects affiliated with [[Johan Casters|Jo]] ([[Attrition (band)|Attrition]]) and has kept producing other influential members of the [[Belgium|Belgian]] music scene such as [[The Lords of Acid]] ever since. He apparently now focusses on writing and producing [[house music|house]] and [[techno music|techno]] records.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums and Mini-Albums===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=A Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Albums and Mini Albums Section]</ref>\n\n* '''''The Gioconda Smile''''' (1985, ARS Records, LP)\n* '''''Hum and Haw''''' (1986, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''Tales of Doom''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, LP/CD)\n* '''''Tetra''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, LP/CD)\n* '''''Existential Despair Methaphysical Distress Ontological Ungludation and Cosmic Meltdown''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, CD)\n* '''''En Grande Col\u00e8re (Seven Tales of Schizophrenia)''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''(Untitled)''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, Cassette)\n* '''''Pity for the Self or We'll Teach You to Dance''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''En Grand Col\u00e8re & Pity for the Self or We'll Teach You to Dance''''' (1989, Antler-Subway,CD)\n* '''''Love Is Colder Than Death''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, LP/CD/Cassette)\n* '''''Complicated - Compilated 84-89''''' (''Best Of Compilation'') (1990, Antler-Subway, LP/CD/Cassette)\n**Stiletto, a Brazilian record label, also released another LP version of this compilation with 5 songs fewer than the Antler-Subway one.\n* '''''Marianne''''' (1991, Antler-Subway,LP/CD/Cassette)\n* '''''Tabula Rasa''''' (1991, Antler-Subway,CD)\n* '''''Delirious''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, CD/Cassette)\n* '''''The Sense of Purpose''''' (2010)\n\n===Singles===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=S Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Singles Section]</ref>\n\n* '''''The Noble Art''''' (1985, ARS Records, 12\")\n* '''''The Gioconda Smile''''' (1985, ARS Records, 12\")\n* '''''Starvation of a Mind''''' (1986, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Radio-Active Flood''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''Timber''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''Tragedy''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Taste of Candy''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Love Is Colder Than Death''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Oblivion''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 12\"/CDM)\n* '''''Toulouse''''' (1990, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\"/CDM)\n* '''''I Didn't Ask''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\")\n* '''''I've Lost a Friend''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\")\n* '''''B-Wall''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Timber (Remix)''''' (1991, Boy Records (Spain), 7\"/12\")\n* '''''Inspire Me''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/12\"/CDS/CDM)\n* '''''Sea of Love''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/CDS)\n* '''''Mercedes Benz''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/CDS)\n\n===Bootleg Compilations===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=B Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Bootlegs Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Po%C3%A9sie+Noire Po\u00e9sie Noire Discography at Discogs]</ref>\n\n''It is to be noted that due to some apparent popularity in some parts of South America, Brazilian labels ''NovoDisc Brasil Industria Fonographica Ltda'' and ''CD+ Nordeste Digital Line/MPR Records'' released two \"'''Best Of Po\u00e9sie Noire'''\" Cds  between 2002 and 2005. Those CDs cover most of the band's career (exclusively focussing on the Antler-Subway years, that is) by use of randomly selected tracks made up of both singles and LP titles.''\n\n* '''''Best of Vol.1''''' (2002, NovoDisc Brasil Industria Fonographica Ltda, Brazil, CD)\n* '''''Best of Vol.2''''' (2005, CD+ Nordeste Digital Line/MPR Records, Brazil, CD)\n* '''''DJ Chesko - New Wave Mix Vol.8''''' (?, Not on Label, Belgium, CD) / Track : '''''Hiroshima Mon Amour'''''\n\n===Compilation Appearances===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/compilations/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Compilations Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Po%C3%A9sie+Noire Po\u00e9sie Noire Discography at Discogs]</ref>\n\n''Due to their domestic popularity, several Belgian [[New wave music|new wave]] or [[Electronic body music|EBM]] compilations have included songs by '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' among their selections. Nevertheless, some of the compilations below are also German, Austrian, Swedish, Spanish, Dutch, British or even American ones thus vouching for the band's relative fame outside the Belgian borders.''\n\n* '''''Mad in Belgium 2''''' (1985, Mad Tapes & Records, Belgium, Cassette) / Track : '''''Mohenjodare'''''\n* '''''The New World Beat''''' (1987, New World Records, Belgium, Double LP) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile (Album version)'''''\n* '''''One of a Number, Part of a Whole''''' (1987, Antler, ? /  Energy Hot Stuff, Sweden, LP) / Track : '''Restraint'''''\n* '''''TotalBeatFactor''''' (1988, Big Nopise In Archgate, UK, EP) / Track : '''''Radio-Active Flood'''''\n* '''''World of Electronic Body Music''''' (1989, Antler, Austria, LP/CD/MC) / Track : '''''Adaptation'''''''\n* '''''Rep\u00e9rages Couleurs - Vol.3 - 1988''''' (1992, 150 BPM Record, ?, CD) / Track : '''Tragedy'''''\n* '''''Spring 1990 Promo Sampler''''' (1990, Antler-Subway, Belgium, Cassette/Sampler/Promo) / Track : '''''Taste of Candy'''''\n* '''''Studio Brussel - Update Live''''' (1992, ART, Austria, CD)  / Track : '''''Just To Be Me Again'''''\n* '''''New Wave Club Class-X 3''''' (1992, Antler-Subway, Belgium, CD/MC) / Track : '''''Gioconda smile (Original)''''' (Also part of CD Box Set, '''''98 New Wave Club Class\u2022X Traxx!!!''''' released in 1996 by [[PIAS Entertainment Group|PIAS]], Belgium)\n* '''''Guitars & Machines''''' (1995, Blanco Y Negro, Spain, Double LP/Double CD) / Track : '''''Pity For The Self'''''\n* '''''New Wave Belgian Class-X''''' (1997, Antler-Subway, Holland, CD) / Track : '''''Po\u00e9sie Noire: Gioconda Smile (Instrumental)'''''\n* '''''Sounds of EBM''''' (1997, Never Records/Antler-Subway, USA, CD) / Track : '''''Adaptation'''''\n* '''''Voll Auf Die Zehn! ''''' (1997, Public Propaganda, ?, Double LP) / Track : '''''Timber'''''\n* '''''EBM Club Classics''''' (1998, Synthtic Symphony/SPV GmbH, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Compjutr Syntax Error'''''\n* '''''Club Wave 2''''' (1999, ARS Production, Belgium, Double CD) / Track '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n* '''''Real Electronic Beats Classix''''' (2001, Roadrunner Arcade, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n** '''''Pity for the Self''''' version of '''''Gioconda Smile''''' with the last minute missing\n* '''''Date Caf\u00e9''''' (2001, Arcade, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Kju:T: All I Wanna Do'''''\n** A track previously known as '''''Kju:T:The Sea''''' when broadcast on Radio Studio Brussels in 1998 after an interview with [[Johan Casters]]\n* '''''Spook Factory''''' (2003, Contrase\u00f1a Records, Spain, Double CD) / Track : '''''Uncertain Smile'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1985''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany,  CD) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1986''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany, CD) / Track : '''''Starvation of the Mind'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1987''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany,  CD) / Track : '''''Timber'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1991''''' (2006, [[EMI]] Music, ?, CD) / Track : '''''Just to Be Me Again'''''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of new wave artists and bands]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.poesienoire.com/ Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site]\n*[https://myspace.com/posienoire Po\u00e9sie Noire Composer and Singer Johan Casters' Myspace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poesie Noire}}\n[[Category:Belgian electronic music groups]]\n[[Category:Electronic body music groups]]\n[[Category:Belgian new wave musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Po\u00e9sie Noire\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Belgium]]\n| genre               = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[dark wave]], [[synthpop]], [[Synthpop|electropop]], [[gothic rock]]\n| years_active        = 1984&ndash;1992\n| label               = [[ARS Records]]<br/>[[Antler-Subway]]<br/>[[EMI]] Belgium<br/>Stiletto<br/>[[Boy Records (Spain)]]\n| associated_acts     = [[TBX]]\n| current_members     = [[Johan Casters]]<br>[[Marianne Valvekens]]<br>[[Herman Gillis]]<br>[[Evanna]]<br>[[Ludo Camberlin aka Carl S. Johansen]] (the [[TBX]] project.)\n}}\n\n'''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' are a [[Belgium|Belgian]] band that rose to prominence in the mid-'80s. Their [[Belgium|Belgian]] origins and tendency to develop a goth-oriented, synthetic, gloomy universe with low-pitched voices - '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' could translate by ''\"Black/Dark Poetry\"'' - had them categorized as [[Electronic body music|EBM]] such as other [[Belgium|Belgian]] members of the 1980s [[electronic music]] scene like [[\u00c0;GRUMH...]] or [[A Split-Second]]. However, much in the manner of various renowned [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Electronic body music|EBM]] bands like [[The Neon Judgement]] and, to some extent, [[Front 242]], they declared, through their music,\na will to step away from the usual [[industrial music|industrial]] aggressiveness that characterized [[Electronic body music]] and developed a more [[mainstream]] accessible dark pop sound that helped them to be regarded as plain [[New wave music|new wave]] or [[Darkwave]].<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/articles/div-GermanArticle/index.html Translation of a German article about the band's influences]</ref><ref>[http://www.lastfm.fr/music/+noredirect/poesie+noire Po\u00e9sie Noire short review at last.fm]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Band Members===\n\nInitially based on seven members, Po\u00e9sie Noire rapidly boiled down to just three hardcore members so as to be finally incarnated by [[Johan Casters]] aka ''\"La B\u00eate Noire\"'' - ''\"The Black/Dark Beast\"'' - (writer, composer and main male singer of the band),  [[Marianne Valvekens]] (co-writer, female vocalist up to the 1991 '''''Marianne''''' album  - and then back on '''''Sense Of Purpose''''' - and keyboard player) and [[Herman Gillis]] (co-writer and mainly the band's guitar player.) As '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' 's fanbase grew along the years, [[Johan Casters|Johan]] and [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] were soon to be given ''\"status nicknames\"'' (probably in tradition of some typically ''\"Goth-spirited\"'' symbolical hierarchy.) Consequently, it did not take long for [[Johan Casters|Casters]] to be considered the band's ''\"Master\"'' to the fans whereas [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] became their ''\"Goddess\"''.\n\nIn 1991, Irish vocalist [[Evanna]] joined the band for the '''''Marianne''''' album because producer [[Ludo Camberlin]] didn't feel [[Marianne Valverken|Marianne]]'s voice was right for the album and [[Evanna]]'s had more warmth and soul to it.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/faq/index.html Marianne and Jo answer to FAQ's]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref>\n\n===Career summary===\n\nVery little is known about how the band actually started their career in music. Nevertheless, they are known to have won the 1985 Breekend Rock Festival (a long-lasting, reputed festival set in [[Bree, Belgium]] that hosted large amounts of prestigious bands such as [[The Smiths]] in 1984 or even [[Slade]] in 2009<ref>[http://www.setlist.fm/venue/breekend-festival-bree-belgium-13d60da1.html The Smiths and Slade at Breekend Festival]</ref>) This domestic victory probably played a part in giving the band a flattering reputation because the following year, Po\u00e9sie Noire started supporting [[Dead Can Dance]]<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/giglist/19860521/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire supporting Dead Can Dance]</ref>\nand [[The Sisters of Mercy]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} on tour, seizing this great opportunity of getting in touch with those huge [[post-punk]], [[goth rock]] bands' audiences to display their own musical conception of darkness to them and have personal gigs set up in the meantime.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's Official Site : Introduction]</ref>\nAlong their years as Po\u00e9sie Noire, the band demonstrated qualities as a prolific act with intensive releases : in just seven years, [[Johan Casters|Casters]], [[Marianne Valvekens|Valvekens]] and [[Herman Gillis|Gillis]] offered their fans 9 albums and mini-albums, 2 official ''best of compilation'', 1 remix compilation and 15 singles which allowed them to appear on various [[Electronic body music|EBM]] or [[New wave music|new wave]] compilations and become genuine figures of the kind throughout their sphere of influence.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=A Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Albums and Mini Albums Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=S Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Singles Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/compilations/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Compilations Section]</ref>\n\n===TBX===\n\nBy 1992, it seems the relations between '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' and their label, Antler-Subway, were not as sound as they used to. Indeed, the record label promised the band they would release yet another album of the band's composition entitled '''''Delirious''''' but this never happened and Antler-Subway finally released [[Johan Casters|Jo]], [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] and newcomer [[Evanna]] from their recording contract instead.\n\nWith the help of [[Ludo Camberlin]] aka Carl S. Johansen, who had been their producer since the 1989 album '''''Love is Colder than Death''''',<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref> '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' changed their name to [[TBX]] (''\"To Be eXcited\"'', that is) and signed to larger label [[EMI]] Belgium that enabled them to release this '''''Delirious''''' album which had been the source of so many issues and changes. But unfortunately for the band, this ''\"new beginning\"'' rapidly ended up unsuccessful - because the band's ''\"music [was not] meant for [the] mass consumption [that ''[[EMI]]'' was used to aiming at]\"'', their official site explains  - and led [[EMI]] Belgium to delete [[TBX]] from their catalog promptly afterwards.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's Official Site : Introduction]</ref> Consequently, for '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''', the bell tolled although they finally returned in 2010 with a new album, '''''Sense Of Purpose'''''.\n\n===Sense Of Purpose===\n\nMore than a decade after the band split, they formed again and started working on a new album, '''''Sense Of Purpose''''',<ref>[http://www.e-musique.com/music/poesie-noire-sense-of-purpose/ e-musique's article about the release of \"Sense of Purpose\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210143634/http://www.e-musique.com/music/poesie-noire-sense-of-purpose/ |date=2010-12-10 }}</ref> finally released in October 2010 under the name that made them famous, '''Po\u00e9sie Noire'''.\n\nThe release of this new opus went along with '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' taking part in the Sinner's Day festival,<ref>[http://www.sinnersday.com/content/line-up Line-up of Sinner's Day festival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907163328/http://www.sinnersday.com/content/line-up |date=2010-09-07 }}</ref> on October 31, 2010, together with such prestigious artists as [[Heaven 17]], [[Nina Hagen]], [[Marc Almond]], [[The Psychedelic Furs]], [[Echo & the Bunnymen]], [[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]], [[The Selecter]], [[Department S (TV series)|Department S]], [[Marky Ramone]], [[Jah Wobble]] or [[Young Gods]].\n\n==Side-Projects and Aftermath==\n\nAfter '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' disbanded, their members carried on musical projects they had been involved in while the band was active, developed new ones or radically turned over a new leaf.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/sideprojects/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Side Projects]</ref>\n\n===Johan Casters===\n\nUsing different aliases (Morton, Joey Morton, Pateke Morton, Ilya Dimitrijevic,Jill (or Jille) Johnson or Alessandro Di Ravo), [[Johan Casters]] has extensively served as a writer, producer and even remixer or editor for various acts and artists. He has developed personal projects from the late 1980s onwards, either alone or with [[Herman Gillis]].\n\nAs a producer or executive producer, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] has been involved in several obscure projects such as [[The Passion of a Primitif]], [[Company of State]], [[Men 2nd]], [[In Sotto Voce]], [[Attrition (band)|Attrition]], [[Ei Mori]], [[Bulgarka]], [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]], [[Pussy Jew]], [[Dee Bass]], [[Translator (music)|Translator]], [[Minimalistix]], [[Orion Too feat. Caitlin]], [[Roxane (music)|Roxane]] and [[Biba Binoche]].\n\nAs a remixer or editor, once again, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] has linked up with a large selection of artists from very obscure to popular favourites as proved by the following list : [[The Neon Judgement]], [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]], [[The Weathermen (Belgian band)|The Weathermen]], [[Jean-Jacques Smoothie]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]].\n\nThough [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] seem to go on making music together, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] was known, in the late 90's, to be working in the field of important musical events coordination and then as [[A&R]] for the Roadrunner turned Mostiko<ref>[http://www.mostiko.be/ Mostiko]</ref>  division of [[Arcade/CNR]].\n\n===Johan Casters and Herman Gillis (and sometimes, Marianne)===\n\nWhile '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' was still active, [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] have been involved as writers and composers in the full or partial development of original or pre-existing projects (with the occasional help of [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]]). The two of them usually worked together though, every once in a while, only one of them would be involved. The massive list of projects the two happen to be behind includes [[In Sotto Voce]], [[Brothers on Acid]], [[Ei Mori]], [[Bulgarka]], [[Trio Balkana]], [[Fruit of Life (music)|Fruit of Life]], [[Erotic Dissidents]], [[Mission Impossible (music)|Mission Impossible]], [[The Brothers (music)|The Brothers]], [[Morton, Sherman and Bellucci]], [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]], [[Opium Monks]], [[Berliner Meisterschaft]], [[The Secrets of China]], [[Kings of Agreppo]], [[Explorers of the Nile]], [[Taste of Sugar feat. K. Finley]], [[TNT Clan]], [[The New Beat Sensation]], [[Msb Sound System]], [[Beat Professor]], [[The Freak Brothers]], [[Student Fashion]], [[Mr. Horse (music)|Mr. Horse]], [[Subway's new Acid House Techno Beat]], [[Balearic Beach]], [[M.S.B.]], [[Supernova (music)|Supernova]], [[Brotherhood of Sleep]], [[The Moneymakers]], [[The Airplane Crashers]], [[Voor Den Broode]], [[German Beat Syndrome]], [[Neue Beat Collectione]], [[Matt's Phantasy Club]], [[Serious ft.JJ Maurie]],  [[Boris Mikulic]], [[J.E.T.]], [[Strictly Nervous]].\n\n===Herman Gillis===\n\nSimilarly to [[Johan Casters|Casters]], while he was already busy co-writing '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' tracks and playing the guitar on them, [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] made sure to develop parallel activities as a producer, writer, composer, programmer and musician using, like his fellow singer, multiple nicknames : Sherman, Herman Sherman, Boris Mikulic and Tessa Rossa. Those activities can be traced back to 1987 until 1994.\n\nAmong the projects he worked for as a writer or co-writer, one should note that he regularly assumed the position of a musician in some of them and took care of programming, keyboards and guitar-playing. Included in this category are [[The Passion of a Primitif]] (1987), [[Company of State]] (1987; 1988), [[In Sotto Voce]] - actually, a genuine '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' side-project posing as a Yugoslavian act. It was incarnated by [[Johan Casters|Jo]] and [[Herman Gillis|Herman]], respectively pretending to be Ilya Dimitrijevic and Boris Mikulic. The point of creating those bogus identities and launching this project was to give a ''\"response to a belgian journalist who found Po\u00e9sie Noire too \"poppy\" \"'' (the official site claims)  - (1987; 1988; 1989), [[Boris Mikulic]] (1990), [[Volt (music)|Volt]] (formerly known as [[Running Cow]]) (1993)...\n\n[[Herman Gillis|Gillis]], much like [[Johan Casters|Casters]], also remixed or edited recordings by various artists either with or without [[Johan Casters|Jo]] : [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]] (1989), [[Take 6 (music)|Take 6]] and [[Take 7]] (19??), [[DWF (music)|DWF]] (1990), [[Wire (band)|Wire]]...\n\nProducing records soon got [[Herman Gillis|Herman]] interested and he quickly had his own production company set up : [[Sherman Productions]]. Among the acts produced by him - either with or without [[Johan Casters|Jo]], once again - one can point out : [[Ei Mori]] (1988), [[Bulgarka]] (1988), [[Danse Macabre (music)|Danse Macabre]] (1988), [[Boris Mikulic]] (1990), [[Spectralyzer]] (1991), [[Trance Too]] (1991), [[Volt (music)|Volt]] (1993-1994) or [[Hypnotyz]] (199?).\n\n[[Herman Gillis]] is also reputed for working on a first hand-made filter known as the [[Sherman Filterbank]]<ref>[http://www.sherman.be/ Sherman Filterbank website]</ref> used by many renowned artists such as [[Air (French band)|Air]], [[The Chemical Brothers]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] or [[The Rolling Stones]].<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/Herman/index.html Herman Gillis]</ref> After the band [[Volt (music)|Volt]] he was involved in split up, [[Herman Gillis|Gillis]] decided he would resign from the music scene and dedicate his energy to the conception of electronic filters and effect boxes of the same kind.\n\n===Marianne Valvekens===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/faq/index.html Marianne and Jo answer to FAQ's]</ref>\n\nContrarily to Jo and Hermann, it seems that record production was never an ambition to Marianne which did not stop her from lending her voice to other '''Po\u00e9sie Noire'''-related projects - being sometimes credited as [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne ''\"the Ice Queen\"'' Valvekens]] - and taking part in the writing and composing of other projects, as well.\n\nAs a vocalist, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]], along with [[Johan Casters|Jo]], took part in the 1986 '''''Mijn-Alarm''''' (''\"Mine-Alarm\"'' in Dutch) project which consisted in gathering the singers from 19 Belgian bands such as [[The Scabs]], [[The Pop Gun]] or [[Siglo XX (band)|Siglo XX]]: each of them were to sing a couple lines from the project's song so as to produce a record whose goal was to raise money for the [[Limburg, Belgium|Limburg]] mineworkers. Later, in 2001, she also gave her voice to [[M&M Project feat.M]]'s ''''''Wide anthem (Sometimes It Hurt)''''' - the final '\"M\"' stood for [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] - one of the many [[Johan Casters|Johan]]-related projects she contributed to also as a writer-composer.\n\nWhen she assumed those positions, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]] used two pseudonyms - Laura Furia and Mateke Porton - which she signed several contributions to various projects with : '''''Strictly Nervous, A Collection Of Acid Jazz - Jazzy House - Jazz Dance''''' (1993), [[M&M Project feat.M]]'s ''''''Wide anthem (Sometimes It Hurt)''''' (2001), [[Orion Too feat.Caitlin]]'s '''''Hope and Wait''''' (2002), '''''So Shy''''' (2002),'''''Travelling''''' (2003) and '''''Making Love For The First Time''''' (2003), [[Biba Binoche]]'s '''''Je Chante pour toi''''' (2004) and [[X3 vs Francis Goya]]'s '''''Rain, the guitar song''''' (2003).\n\nAround 2003, she was also said to be writing a book but no further piece of news has ever surfaced about it since then.\n\nHowever, it seems that from the late 1990s onwards, [[Marianne Valvekens|Marianne]]'s main occupation has been as a worker in some kind of employment agency.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/introduction/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's official site introduction]</ref>\n\n===Evanna===\n\nAfter her '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''' years, it seems [[Evanna]] has not been heard of again in the music-making business\n\n===Ludo Camberlin/Carl S. Johansen===\n\nWhile living the '''Po\u00e9sie Noire/TBX''' episode, [[Ludo Camberlin]] also worked as a producer on projects affiliated with [[Johan Casters|Jo]] ([[Attrition (band)|Attrition]]) and has kept producing other influential members of the [[Belgium|Belgian]] music scene such as [[The Lords of Acid]] ever since. He apparently now focusses on writing and producing [[house music|house]] and [[techno music|techno]] records.<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/band/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire's band members]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums and Mini-Albums===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=A Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Albums and Mini Albums Section]</ref>\n\n* '''''The Gioconda Smile''''' (1985, ARS Records, LP)\n* '''''Hum and Haw''''' (1986, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''Tales of Doom''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, LP/CD)\n* '''''Tetra''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, LP/CD)\n* '''''Existential Despair Methaphysical Distress Ontological Ungludation and Cosmic Meltdown''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, CD)\n* '''''En Grande Col\u00e8re (Seven Tales of Schizophrenia)''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''(Untitled)''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, Cassette)\n* '''''Pity for the Self or We'll Teach You to Dance''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, LP)\n* '''''En Grand Col\u00e8re & Pity for the Self or We'll Teach You to Dance''''' (1989, Antler-Subway,CD)\n* '''''Love Is Colder Than Death''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, LP/CD/Cassette)\n* '''''Complicated - Compilated 84-89''''' (''Best Of Compilation'') (1990, Antler-Subway, LP/CD/Cassette)\n**Stiletto, a Brazilian record label, also released another LP version of this compilation with 5 songs fewer than the Antler-Subway one.\n* '''''Marianne''''' (1991, Antler-Subway,LP/CD/Cassette)\n* '''''Tabula Rasa''''' (1991, Antler-Subway,CD)\n* '''''Delirious''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, CD/Cassette)\n* '''''The Sense of Purpose''''' (2010)\n\n===Singles===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=S Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Singles Section]</ref>\n\n* '''''The Noble Art''''' (1985, ARS Records, 12\")\n* '''''The Gioconda Smile''''' (1985, ARS Records, 12\")\n* '''''Starvation of a Mind''''' (1986, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Radio-Active Flood''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''Timber''''' (1987, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''Tragedy''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Taste of Candy''''' (1988, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Love Is Colder Than Death''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 12\")\n* '''''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Oblivion''''' (1989, Antler-Subway, 12\"/CDM)\n* '''''Toulouse''''' (1990, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\"/CDM)\n* '''''I Didn't Ask''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\")\n* '''''I've Lost a Friend''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\"/12\")\n* '''''B-Wall''''' (1991, Antler-Subway, 7\")\n* '''''Timber (Remix)''''' (1991, Boy Records (Spain), 7\"/12\")\n* '''''Inspire Me''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/12\"/CDS/CDM)\n* '''''Sea of Love''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/CDS)\n* '''''Mercedes Benz''''' (as '''[[TBX]]''') (1992, [[EMI]] Belgium/Creastars, 7\"/CDS)\n\n===Bootleg Compilations===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/php/disco.php?typeofrecord=B Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Bootlegs Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Po%C3%A9sie+Noire Po\u00e9sie Noire Discography at Discogs]</ref>\n\n''It is to be noted that due to some apparent popularity in some parts of South America, Brazilian labels ''NovoDisc Brasil Industria Fonographica Ltda'' and ''CD+ Nordeste Digital Line/MPR Records'' released two \"'''Best Of Po\u00e9sie Noire'''\" Cds  between 2002 and 2005. Those CDs cover most of the band's career (exclusively focussing on the Antler-Subway years, that is) by use of randomly selected tracks made up of both singles and LP titles.''\n\n* '''''Best of Vol.1''''' (2002, NovoDisc Brasil Industria Fonographica Ltda, Brazil, CD)\n* '''''Best of Vol.2''''' (2005, CD+ Nordeste Digital Line/MPR Records, Brazil, CD)\n* '''''DJ Chesko - New Wave Mix Vol.8''''' (?, Not on Label, Belgium, CD) / Track : '''''Hiroshima Mon Amour'''''\n\n===Compilation Appearances===\n<ref>[http://www.poesienoire.com/compilations/index.html Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site : Compilations Section]</ref><ref>[http://www.discogs.com/artist/Po%C3%A9sie+Noire Po\u00e9sie Noire Discography at Discogs]</ref>\n\n''Due to their domestic popularity, several Belgian [[New wave music|new wave]] or [[Electronic body music|EBM]] compilations have included songs by '''Po\u00e9sie Noire''' among their selections. Nevertheless, some of the compilations below are also German, Austrian, Swedish, Spanish, Dutch, British or even American ones thus vouching for the band's relative fame outside the Belgian borders.''\n\n* '''''Mad in Belgium 2''''' (1985, Mad Tapes & Records, Belgium, Cassette) / Track : '''''Mohenjodare'''''\n* '''''The New World Beat''''' (1987, New World Records, Belgium, Double LP) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile (Album version)'''''\n* '''''One of a Number, Part of a Whole''''' (1987, Antler, ? /  Energy Hot Stuff, Sweden, LP) / Track : '''Restraint'''''\n* '''''TotalBeatFactor''''' (1988, Big Nopise In Archgate, UK, EP) / Track : '''''Radio-Active Flood'''''\n* '''''World of Electronic Body Music''''' (1989, Antler, Austria, LP/CD/MC) / Track : '''''Adaptation'''''''\n* '''''Rep\u00e9rages Couleurs - Vol.3 - 1988''''' (1992, 150 BPM Record, ?, CD) / Track : '''Tragedy'''''\n* '''''Spring 1990 Promo Sampler''''' (1990, Antler-Subway, Belgium, Cassette/Sampler/Promo) / Track : '''''Taste of Candy'''''\n* '''''Studio Brussel - Update Live''''' (1992, ART, Austria, CD)  / Track : '''''Just To Be Me Again'''''\n* '''''New Wave Club Class-X 3''''' (1992, Antler-Subway, Belgium, CD/MC) / Track : '''''Gioconda smile (Original)''''' (Also part of CD Box Set, '''''98 New Wave Club Class\u2022X Traxx!!!''''' released in 1996 by [[PIAS Entertainment Group|PIAS]], Belgium)\n* '''''Guitars & Machines''''' (1995, Blanco Y Negro, Spain, Double LP/Double CD) / Track : '''''Pity For The Self'''''\n* '''''New Wave Belgian Class-X''''' (1997, Antler-Subway, Holland, CD) / Track : '''''Po\u00e9sie Noire: Gioconda Smile (Instrumental)'''''\n* '''''Sounds of EBM''''' (1997, Never Records/Antler-Subway, USA, CD) / Track : '''''Adaptation'''''\n* '''''Voll Auf Die Zehn! ''''' (1997, Public Propaganda, ?, Double LP) / Track : '''''Timber'''''\n* '''''EBM Club Classics''''' (1998, Synthtic Symphony/SPV GmbH, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Compjutr Syntax Error'''''\n* '''''Club Wave 2''''' (1999, ARS Production, Belgium, Double CD) / Track '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n* '''''Real Electronic Beats Classix''''' (2001, Roadrunner Arcade, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n** '''''Pity for the Self''''' version of '''''Gioconda Smile''''' with the last minute missing\n* '''''Date Caf\u00e9''''' (2001, Arcade, ?, Double CD) / Track : '''''Kju:T: All I Wanna Do'''''\n** A track previously known as '''''Kju:T:The Sea''''' when broadcast on Radio Studio Brussels in 1998 after an interview with [[Johan Casters]]\n* '''''Spook Factory''''' (2003, Contrase\u00f1a Records, Spain, Double CD) / Track : '''''Uncertain Smile'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1985''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany,  CD) / Track : '''''Gioconda Smile'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1986''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany, CD) / Track : '''''Starvation of the Mind'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1987''''' (2005, [[Universal Music]], Germany,  CD) / Track : '''''Timber'''''\n* '''''Bel80 1991''''' (2006, [[EMI]] Music, ?, CD) / Track : '''''Just to Be Me Again'''''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of new wave artists and bands]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.poesienoire.com/ Po\u00e9sie Noire Official Site]\n*[https://myspace.com/posienoire Po\u00e9sie Noire Composer and Singer Johan Casters' Myspace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poesie Noire}}\n[[Category:Belgian electronic music groups]]\n[[Category:Electronic body music groups]]\n[[Category:Belgian new wave musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po%C3%A9sie_Noire"}
{"title_page": "Jade Foret", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian model|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name          = Jade Foret\n| image         = Une_photo_de_Jade_Foret_lors_de_ses_vacances_aux_USA_en_juillet_2011_2014-01-28_07-24.JPG\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Jade Foret on holidays in the US - July 2011\n| alt           = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1990|09|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1990|09|26|df=y}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| ethnicity     = \n| height        = {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} \n| hair_color    = brown\n| eye_color     = blue\n| agency        = Iconic Management\n| spouse        = <!-- {{marriage|name|start|end}} -->\n| relatives     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|website}} -->\n}}\n'''Jade Foret''' (born 26 September 1990) is a Belgian model whose family roots are in [[France]].<ref name=\"nouvel_obs\">[http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/actualite/people/20110720.OBS7356/photos-videos-jade-foret-nouveau-phenomene-du-web.html PHOTOS-VIDEOS. Jade Foret, nouveau ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne du web] ''NouvelObs.com'' 2011-07-20</ref> She is the wife of French businessman [[Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re]].<ref name=\"jade_foret\">[http://lexpansion.lexpress.fr/entreprise/lagardere-le-grand-patron-qui-fait-le-buzz_259108.html Lagard\u00e8re, le grand patron qui fait le buzz] ''[[L'Expansion]]'' - 2011-07-20</ref> \n\n==Biography==\nShe is the daughter of Ma\u00eft\u00e9 Foret, the fourth child of a family of five.<ref name=\"nouvel_obs\" /> She started modelling at the young age of 12<ref name=\"mannequin\">[http://essentiellemagazines.lalibre.be/n69/dossier.html ELLES FONT LA MODE] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926175446/http://essentiellemagazines.lalibre.be/n69/dossier.html |date=2011-09-26 }} - ''La Libre Essentielle'' F\u00e9vrier 2005</ref>  with the Newmodels agency in 2003. At age 13, in 2004, she became famous in Belgium for a [[Halterneck|backless]] picture which was displayed as a gigantic poster for the Levis paint brand (100 m by 20) on the [[Madou Plaza Tower]] in [[Brussels]].<ref name=\"tour_madou\">[http://www.dhnet.be/dhjournal/archives_det.phtml?id=375111 Elle a tout d'une grande] - ''dh.be'' 14/07/2004</ref> At the same age, she went on the catwalk for [[Armani]] in Italy.<ref name=\"nyjsm\">[http://www.nyjsm.com/celebrity/Jade_Foret_Interview.cfm Interview with Jade Foret] ''The New York Journal of Style and Medecine'' - Matthew Vasey, MD - November 2, 2010</ref>         \n\nForet had a short and stormy liaison with soccer player [[\u00c9mile Mpenza]],<ref name=\"mpenza\">[http://www.lesdessousdusport.fr/jade-foret-relance-la-carriere-d-emile-mpenza-6770 Jade Foret relance la carri\u00e8re d'Emile Mpenza] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810085729/http://www.lesdessousdusport.fr/jade-foret-relance-la-carriere-d-emile-mpenza-6770 |date=2011-08-10 }} LDDS.fr 12 ao\u00fbt 2009</ref> which concluded bitterly.<ref name=\"mpenza2\">[http://www.dhnet.be/sports/football/article/289681/affaire-mpenza-jade-foret-emile-attaque-son-ex-en-justice.html Affaire Mpenza - Jade Foret: Emile attaque son ex en justice] ''DH.be'' 19/11/2009</ref> She continued working as a top model and decided to move to New York. She joined the agency [[One Management]].<ref name=\"le_soir\">[http://archives.lesoir.be/jade-forest-top-modele-c-8217-est-parfois-l-8217-enfer-_t-20091214-00RD1N.html Jade Forest: \u00ab Top mod\u00e8le, c\u2019est parfois l\u2019enfer ! \u00bb] - ''lesoir.be'' 14/12/2009</ref> She also tried singing and played bit parts in films and on television.\n\nIn 2010 she met businessman Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re and became his partner.<ref name=\"jade_foret\" /> They both appeared in a short [[making-of]] of a photo shoot in Lagard\u00e8re's country residence in [[Rambouillet]]<ref name=\"rambouillet\">[http://soirmag.lesoir.be/jade-foret-son-shooting-sexy-pour-soirmagbe-vid%C3%A9o-2011-07-19-7570 Jade Foret: son shooting sexy pour soirmag.be ! (vid\u00e9o)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722182711/http://soirmag.lesoir.be/jade-foret-son-shooting-sexy-pour-soirmagbe-vid%C3%A9o-2011-07-19-7570 |date=2011-07-22 }} ''[[Le Soir]]'' Mardi 19 Juillet 2011 - Gery Brusselmans</ref> in July 2011 for the Belgian daily ''[[Le Soir]]''.<ref name=\"net\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/23/business/global/heir-apparent-at-eads-appears-in-internet-video.html Heir Apparent at EADS Stirs Controversy With Web Video] - ''[[The New York Times]]'' Nicola Clark - July 22, 2011</ref> This video became an instant Internet phenomenon.<ref name=\"nouvel_obs\" /> It also led some employees from the industrial conglomerate of Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re to challenge his ability to manage the group.<ref name=\"the_australian\">[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/executive-lifestyle/so-shoot-me/story-e6frg9zo-1226101190927 So shoot me] - ''The Times'' - July 25, 2011</ref>\n\nIn May 2012 Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re confirmed that the couple will marry soon and was expecting a baby in September 2012.<ref name=\"le_point\">{{cite news | first=Emmanuel | last=Berretta | title=Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re : un mariage, un b\u00e9b\u00e9 et une assembl\u00e9e g\u00e9n\u00e9rale | url=http://www.lepoint.fr/chroniqueurs-du-point/emmanuel-berretta/arnaud-lagardere-un-mariage-un-bebe-et-une-assemblee-generale-03-05-2012-1457788_52.php | location = Paris | agency= | newspaper=[[Le Point]] | date=3 May 2012 }}</ref> The baby girl, Liva, was born on 16 September 2012. They married in Paris on 24 May 2013.<ref>[http://www.rtl.be/people/people/news/754810/jade-foret-et-arnaud-lagardere-se-sont-maries-aujourd-hui-a-paris Jade Foret et Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re se sont mari\u00e9s aujourd'hui \u00e0 Paris]</ref>\n\nThey have also a second daughter, Mila (born 9 March 2014) and a son, Nolan (born 16 January 2016)\n\n==Filmography==\n*''Louis la Brocante'' - \"Louis et la belle brocante\" (2008) : ''girl at the bar''\n*''Traceless'' (Sans laisser de traces) (2010) : ''Russian girl''\n\n==Books==\n===Graphic novels===\n====''Amber Blake'' series====\n*''La Fille de Merton Castle'' (2017) with [[Jackson Guice]] - [[Gl\u00e9nat Editions]] - {{ISBN|978-2344016190}}\n*''Op\u00e9ration Cleverland'' (to be published) with [[Jackson Guice]] - Gl\u00e9nat Editions\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=4194636}}\n{{portal|fashion|Belgium}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foret, Jade}}\n[[Category:Belgian female models]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of French descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian model|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox model\n| name          = Jade Foret\n| image         = Une_photo_de_Jade_Foret_lors_de_ses_vacances_aux_USA_en_juillet_2011_2014-01-28_07-24.JPG\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Jade Foret on holidays in the US - July 2011\n| alt           = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1990|09|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1990|09|26|df=y}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| ethnicity     = \n| height        = {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} \n| hair_color    = brown\n| eye_color     = blue\n| agency        = Iconic Management\n| spouse        = <!-- {{marriage|name|start|end}} -->\n| relatives     = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|website}} -->\n}}\n'''Jade Foret''' (born 26 September 1990) is a Belgian model whose family roots are in [[France]].<ref name=\"nouvel_obs\">[http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/actualite/people/20110720.OBS7356/photos-videos-jade-foret-nouveau-phenomene-du-web.html PHOTOS-VIDEOS. Jade Foret, nouveau ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne du web] ''NouvelObs.com'' 2011-07-20</ref> She is the wife of French businessman [[Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re]].<ref name=\"jade_foret\">[