bl\u00e9e g\u00e9n\u00e9rale | url=http://www.lepoint.fr/chroniqueurs-du-point/emmanuel-berretta/arnaud-lagardere-un-mariage-un-bebe-et-une-assemblee-generale-03-05-2012-1457788_52.php | location = Paris | agency= | newspaper=[[Le Point]] | date=3 May 2012 }}</ref> The baby girl, Liva, was born on 16 September 2012. They married in Paris on 24 May 2013.<ref>[http://www.rtl.be/people/people/news/754810/jade-foret-et-arnaud-lagardere-se-sont-maries-aujourd-hui-a-paris Jade Foret et Arnaud Lagard\u00e8re se sont mari\u00e9s aujourd'hui \u00e0 Paris]</ref>\n\nThey have also a second daughter, Mila (born 9 March 2014) and a son, Nolan (born 16 January 2016)\n\n==Filmography==\n*''Louis la Brocante'' - \"Louis et la belle brocante\" (2008) : ''girl at the bar''\n*''Traceless'' (Sans laisser de traces) (2010) : ''Russian girl''\n\n==Books==\n===Graphic novels===\n====''Amber Blake'' series====\n*''La Fille de Merton Castle'' (2017) with [[Jackson Guice]] - [[Gl\u00e9nat Editions]] - {{ISBN|978-2344016190}}\n*''Op\u00e9ration Cleverland'' (to be published) with [[Jackson Guice]] - Gl\u00e9nat Editions\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=4194636}}\n{{portal|fashion|Belgium}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foret, Jade}}\n[[Category:Belgian female models]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian people of French descent]]\n", "name_user": "Casseb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:whole paragraph seems rather tabloid-like, but just fixing a typo for now", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jade_Foret"}
{"title_page": "Jose Fabella Memorial School", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Dr. Jose Fabella Memorial Hospital|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Jose Fabella Memorial School\n | native_name             = {{small|''Pang-alaalang Paaralang Jose Fabella''}}\n | logo                    = JFMS_Logo.jpg\n | streetaddress           = Welfareville Compound\n | city                    = [[Mandaluyong City]]\n | state                   = [[Metro Manila]]\n | zipcode                 = 1550\n | country                 = [[Philippines]]\n | coordinates             = {{coord|14|35|06|N|121|02|04|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n | campus                  = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n | language                = [[English language|English]], [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n | other_name              = Welfareville School\n | type                    = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n | established             = December 3, 1925<br /><small>{{nowrap|({{age in years and days|December 3, 1925|sep=and}})}}</small>\n | founder                 = [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]]\n | oversight               = [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]]\n | principal               = Olivia L. Pagurayan\n | faculty                 = 75 (2015)\n | grades                  = K to 12\n | enrollment              = 2,622\n | enrollment_as_of        = 2014\n | nickname                = Fabellans\n | newspaper               = ''The Fabellan Journal''\n | website                 = {{URL|jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com}}\n | logo_alt                = Official Logo of Jose Fabella Memorial School\n | colors                  = Green and yellow {{color box|green}}{{color box|yellow}}\n | song                    = The JFMS March\n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n}}\n\n[[File:Jose-fabella.jpg|thumb|Dr. [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]], the Father of Public Health and Social Welfare in the Philippines.]]\nThe '''Jose Fabella Memorial School''' ([[Filipino language|Filipino]]: ''Pang-alaalang Paaralang Jose Fabella''; abbreviated as '''JFMS''' and commonly known as '''Fabella''') is a [[Public education|public]] integrated [[special school]] located in Welfareville Compound, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] in [[Metro Manila]],  [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/|title=About Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Founded on December 3, 1925 as the Welfareville School, it is considered as one of the oldest [[School|educational institutions]] in [[Mandaluyong City]] and is currently one of the four public [[Special education|special schools]] in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncda.gov.ph/list-of-sped-centers/government-special-schools/|title=Government Special Schools|last=|first=|date=2019|website=National Council on Disability Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It serves as the [[umbrella organization]] of 12 [[special education]] units located in different parts of [[Metro Manila]] and [[Rizal]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/organization/|title=Organization of Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and offers [[kindergarten]], [[Primary education|elementary]], [[Secondary education|secondary]] ([[Middle school|junior]] and senior high school) and [[Special education|special educatio]]<nowiki/>n to regular [[student]]s and [[Special education|students with additional needs]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\nThe history of JFMS traces its roots to Act No. 267 enacted by the [[Philippine Legislature]] on January 10, 1917 which established the first [[government]] [[orphanage]] and marked the beginning of the national child welfare program in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Pangan|first=Angela Maria|date=1999|title=Looking into the Philippine foster care experience: Trends and challenges|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/children-australia/article/div-classtitlelooking-into-the-philippine-foster-care-experience-trends-and-challengesdiv/CB173688CA6B85C580B886DFD337370D|journal=Children Australia|volume=24|issue=4|pages=76\u201388|doi=10.1017/S1035077200009421|issn=1035-0772|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Bunye|first=Alfredo M.|date=January\u2013March 1958|title=The Philippine Prison System|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=yKsiAQAAIAAJ&dq|journal=Unitas|volume=31|issue=1|pages=121\u2013169|via=}}</ref> On December 3, 1924, Act No. 3203 was passed placing \"public institutions intended for the care, custody, correction, education and training of [[orphan]]s, homeless, neglected, [[Child abuse|abused]], defective and [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquent]] children under the administration and supervision of the Bureau of Public Welfare\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Murillo|first=Agapita|date=1944|title=Public Welfare Services in the Philippines, 1898-1941|journal=Social Service Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=189\u2013204|jstor=30014210|doi=10.1086/634860}}</ref> On January 6, 1925, the Bureau of Public Welfare purchased a 56-hectare land in the municipality of [[Mandaluyong|San Felipe Neri]], [[Rizal|Province of Rizal]], where the [[government]]'s child-caring institutions were established on December 3, 1925 and collectively called Welfareville Institutions.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Glimpses of What Was Welfareville \"The Children's Village\" by Recollection|last=Ramos|first=Ike|date=June 1988|work=The Welfarevillians|access-date=|volume=1|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zrvvwQEACAAJ|title=Annual Report of the Governor General of the Philippine Islands, 1925|last=|first=|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1927|isbn=|location=Washington|pages=76}}</ref> It originally consisted of 1) the Philippine Training School for Boys and the Philippine Training School for Girls, which catered to [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquent]] boys and girls; 2) [[orphanage]], to provide for the care of destitute children and children of [[Leprosy|leprous]] parents; 3) nursery for non-leprous children below two years of age, to provide care of children of [[Leprosy|leprous]] parents born in [[Culion leper colony|Culion]];<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arcilla|first=Jose S.|date=2009|title=The Culion Leper Colony, 1900s-1970s|journal=Philippine Studies|volume=57|issue=2|pages=307\u2013326|jstor=42634012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.dukeupress.edu/colonial-pathologies|title=Colonial Pathologies: American Tropical Medicine, Race, and Hygiene in the Philippines|last=Anderson|first=Warwick|date=2006|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0822388081|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> 4) home for the [[Intellectual disability|mentally-defective]] children, to provide care and treatment of boys and girls who are [[Intellectual disability|mentally defective]]; and 5) home for the aged and the infirm, to provide [[Nursing home care|institutional care]] for such persons who are [[Extreme poverty|destitute]].<ref name=\":3\" /> A school was also established, called Welfareville School, to provide [[Education|academic instruction and vocational training]] to [[orphan]]s and wards of Welfareville Institutions.\n\nDue to the increasing number of [[orphan]]s and other beneficiaries admitted to Welfareville Institutions, a sum of \u20b160,000 was appropriated by the end of 1929 for the construction of additional buildings for [[orphan]]s, [[Cripple|invalids]], and aged people.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=9gErAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Public Laws Enacted by the Philippine Legislature during the Period August 9, 1929 to February 7, 1930|last=|first=|publisher=Bureau of Printing|year=1930|isbn=|volume=25|location=Manila, Philippines|pages=522}}</ref> A sum of \u20b121,000 was also appropriated by virtue of Commonwealth Act No. 61 enacted on October 20, 1936 for the continued operation and maintenance of Welfareville Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1936/10/20/commonwealth-act-no-61/|title=Commonwealth Act No. 61|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1936|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 1958, President [[Carlos P. Garcia]] issued Executive Order No. 326 reorganizing the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] (an agency created following the abolition of Bureau of Public Welfare) which used to administer and supervise the Welfareville Institutions. This resulted to the transfer of oversight of Welfareville School to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]]. Under this arrangement, the Welfareville School provided [[Education|formal education]] to [[orphan]]s and wards of Welfareville Institutions which it subsequently called \"[[special education]] units,<nowiki>''</nowiki> with the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] retaining jurisdiction of the institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1958/12/11/executive-order-no-326-s-1958/|title=Executive Order No. 326, s. 1958|last=|first=|date=December 11, 1958|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nFor many years since its establishment, there have been calls to change the name of the school to remove the [[Social stigma|stigma]] associated with it as the \"dumping ground of society's rejects.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/about/history/|title=History of Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1969/01/27/ferdinand-e-marcos-fourth-state-of-the-nation-address-january-27-1969/|title=President Ferdinand Marcos' Fourth State of the Nation Address|last=|first=|date=January 7, 1969|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On June 21, 1963, Republic Act No. 3576 was passed changing the name of Welfareville School to Jose Fabella Memorial School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra1963/ra_3576_1963.html|title=Republic Act No. 3576|last=|first=|date=2019|website=The LawPhil Project of Arellano Law Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/republic-acts/ra-no-3576.php|title=Republic Act No 3576|last=|first=|date=2019|website=The Corporis Juris|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This was in honor of Dr. [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]], the first Commissioner of the Bureau of Public Welfare<ref name=\":3\" /> and considered as the Father of Public Health and Social Welfare in the Philippines,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oqIMAQAAMAAJ|title=White Hero: Dr. Jose F. Fabella, 1888-1945, Father of Public Health and Social Welfare|last=Ricafrente|first=Gerardo S.|publisher=Richforehead Publications|year=2008|isbn=9789719236443|location=Mandaluyong City, Philippines|pages=}}</ref> who laid the plan for the development of Welfareville Institutions.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/node/1659|title=Dr. Jose F. Fabella|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an agreement between the [[Philippine]] [[government]] and the [[United Nations Children's Fund]] to upgrade the child welfare services in the Philippines, Republic Act No. 5260 was enacted on June 15, 1968 which called for the [[Decentralization|dispersion]] and [[decentralization]] of the Welfareville Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicacts/republicactno5260.html|title=Republic Act No. 5260|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Chan Robles Virtual Law Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This led to the dispersal of the [[special education]] units of JFMS in [[Metro Manila]] and outskirts. On August 11, 2011, Republic Act No. 9155 was passed which placed JFMS under the Schools Division Office of [[Mandaluyong City]].\n\nAt present, JFMS is one of the four public [[Special education|special schools]] in the [[Philippines]]<ref name=\":1\" /> and consists of a flagship [[campus]] in [[Mandaluyong City]] which caters to regular students and students with learning disabilities and behavioral problems and 12 [[special education]] units located in different parts of [[Metro Manila]] and [[Rizal]] which cater to students with [[Special education|additional needs]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n===    JFMS Units ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Unit\n!Location\n!Learners' Profile\n|-\n|Nayon ng Kabataan\n|Welfareville Compound, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|[[Child abuse|abused]], [[Orphan|orphaned]], [[Child abandonment|abandoned]], [[Child neglect|neglected]] and [[Child sexual abuse|exploited]] children aged 7 to 17 years old\n|-\n|Bagong Sinag Special School\n|[[National Center for Mental Health]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|[[Intellectual disability|mentally-handicapped]] patients\n|-\n|Jose Fabella Center\n|Correctional Road, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|strandees, [[Homelessness|transients]], [[Vagrancy|vagrants]] and [[Mendicant|mendicants]]\n|-\n|[[Dangerous Drugs Board]]\u2014[[European Union]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Center\n|[[Diliman, Quezon City]]\n|people with [[Substance dependence|drug dependence]]\n|-\n|CRIBS Foundation, Inc.\n|Industrial Valley, [[Marikina|Marikina City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]], [[Child neglect|neglected]], surrendered and female minor survivors of [[child abuse]]\n|-\n|Special Learning Center\n|City Hall, [[Quezon City]]\n|children with [[Juvenile delinquency|behavioral problems]]\n|-\n|[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Center\n|Bicutan, [[Taguig|Taguig City]]\n|children and adults with [[Addiction|drug addiction]]\n|-\n|Elsie Gaches Village\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]] and [[Child neglect|neglected]] children with mild to severe [[Intellectual disability|mental disorders]]\n|-\n|National Training School for Girls\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]] female street children\n|-\n|National Training School for Boys\n|[[Tanay, Rizal]]\n|[[Juvenile delinquency|male juveniles]] in conflict with the law aged 9 to 17 years old\n|-\n|Haven for Children\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|boys aged 7 to 13 recovering from [[substance abuse]]\n|-\n|Molave Youth Homes\n|[[Quezon City|Diliman, Quezon City]]\n|children with [[Juvenile delinquency|behavioral problems]]\n|}\n\n==Administration==\n{| style=\"float:right; margin:1em; width:18em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; padding:2px; bg-color=yellow; text-align:right;\"\n|- style=\"background:#026f27; text-align:center;\"\n|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''School Principals of <br />Jose Fabella Memorial School'''</span>\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Maximo C. Songco'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Ignacio F. Lim'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Ignacio N. Alcantara'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Gerardo A. Consolacion'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Fortunata A. Rabang'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Aida S. Damian*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Alicia B. Reyes*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Arsenia C. Lara*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Erdelinda G. Diaz*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Olivia L. Pagurayan'''\n----<nowiki>*</nowiki>''---served as Officer-in-Charge of the Office of the Principal''\n|}\n\nSince its establishment as Welfareville School on December 3, 1925, the [[school]] was governed by Bureau of Public Welfare under the Department of Public Instruction from 1925 to 1938 and under the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health and Public Welfare]] from 1939 to 1946. On October 4, 1947, the administration and supervision of Welfareville School was transferred to the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Commission]] which replaced the Bureau of Public Welfare after its abolition.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=http://digitallibrary.usc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15799coll39/id/232620/rec/1|title=The Philippines' Social Welfare Administration: A Historical Account of its Formation, 1946-1956.|last=de Guzman|first=Leonora|publisher=Master's Thesis, University of Southern California|date=January 1964|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> On January 3, 1951, President [[Elpidio Quirino]] issued Executive Order No. 396 converting the Social Welfare Commission into [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1951/01/03/executive-order-no-396-s-1951/|title=Executive Order No. 396, s. 1951|last=|first=|date=January 3, 1951|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, thereby making it the governing agency of Welfareville School. Following the reorganization of the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] on December 11, 1958, the oversight of Welfareville School was transferred to the Special Subjects and Services Division, and later to the Special Education Unit of the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]].<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nAt present, JFMS is directly supervised by the Schools Division Office of [[Mandaluyong City]] which oversees all public and private elementary and secondary [[School|educational institutions]], including [[Alternative Learning System (Philippines)|alternative learning systems]] in its jurisdiction.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depedmandaluyong.org/schools/|title=Schools of DepEd Mandaluyong|last=|first=|date=2019|website=DepEd Mandaluyong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> JFMS is headed by a [[Special education|Special Education]] [[Principal (education)|Principal]] with the assistance of three Assistant [[Principal (education)|Principals]], for [[Primary school|Grade School]], [[Middle school|Junior High School]], and [[Secondary school|Senior High School]], all of whom are designated by the Schools Division Office. The [[special education]] units of JFMS are headed by Teachers-in-Charge designated by the [[Principal (education)|principal]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nJFMS is broadly organized into three [[Academic department|departments]]: [[Primary school|Grade School]], [[Middle school|Junior High School]], and [[Secondary school|Senior High School]], each headed by a [[Academic department|department]] head; 12 grade levels: Grades 1 to 12, each headed by a grade level chairperson; and eight subject areas for [[Primary school|Grade School]] and [[Middle school|Junior High School]], each headed by a subject area coordinator.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAs of 2015, JFMS had a total of 104 personnel complement, including 39 elementary and 36 secondary [[special education]] [[teacher]]s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Campus==\nThe main [[campus]] of JFMS sits on a portion of 56-hectare [[government]] land which is now the sprawling Welfareville Compound.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other [[Government agency|government agencies]] located along the vicinity of JFMS include the Nayon ng Kabataan (front), Welfareville Commission (left) and Commission on Population (right). The units of JFMS are located in [[Metro Manila]], except for the National Training School for Boys which is situated in [[Tanay, Rizal]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==People==\nPeople affiliated with JFMS as [[student]]s, [[Alumnus|graduates]], and [[Teacher|teaching]] and non-teaching personnel are called \"Fabellans.\" [[Alumnus|Graduates]] of the school are inducted annually as members of the Jose Fabella Memorial School Alumni Association. Olivia L. Pagurayan, a former [[professor]] of [[special education]] at [[Philippine Normal University]], serves as its current [[principal (education)|principal]].\n\n===    Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc. ===\nFounded in 1955 as Orphans' Association, the Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc. is a non-stock and [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]] of former [[orphan]]s, wards, and employees of Welfareville Institutions and [[Alumnus|graduates]] of Welfareville School.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc.|last=|first=|date=June 1988|work=The Welfarevillians|access-date=|volume=1|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Jfms bust.jpg|Bust of Dr. Jose Fabella\nFile:Main quadrangle.jpg|JFMS quadrangle facing the administration building\nFile:High school building.jpg|One of the high school buildings\nFile:JFMS SPED Building.jpg|Special education building \nFile:JFMS-NTSG.jpg|Signage of JFMS at National Training School for Girls in Alabang, Muntinlupa City\nFile:Haven for Children.jpg|JFMS building at Haven for Children in Alabang, Muntinlupa City \nFile:JFMS 1960.jpg|Former Gabaldon building, ca. 1980s\nFile:Jfms tower.jpg|Former dormitory of Philippine Training School for Boys, ca. 1960s\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{portal|Philippines|Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Special schools in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Schools in Mandaluyong]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1925]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Dr. Jose Fabella Memorial Hospital|}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Jose Fabella Memorial School\n | native_name             = {{small|''Pang-alaalang Paaralang Jose Fabella''}}\n | logo                    = \n | streetaddress           = Welfareville Compound\n | city                    = [[Mandaluyong City]]\n | state                   = [[Metro Manila]]\n | zipcode                 = 1550\n | country                 = [[Philippines]]\n | coordinates             = {{coord|14|35|06|N|121|02|04|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n | campus                  = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n | language                = [[English language|English]], [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n | other_name              = Welfareville School\n | type                    = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n | established             = December 3, 1925<br /><small>{{nowrap|({{age in years and days|December 3, 1925|sep=and}})}}</small>\n | founder                 = [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]]\n | oversight               = [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]]\n | principal               = Olivia L. Pagurayan\n | faculty                 = 75 (2015)\n | grades                  = K to 12\n | enrollment              = 2,622\n | enrollment_as_of        = 2014\n | nickname                = Fabellans\n | newspaper               = ''The Fabellan Journal''\n | website                 = {{URL|jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com}}\n | logo_alt                = Official Logo of Jose Fabella Memorial School\n | colors                  = Green and yellow {{color box|green}}{{color box|yellow}}\n | song                    = The JFMS March\n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n}}\n\n[[File:Jose-fabella.jpg|thumb|Dr. [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]], the Father of Public Health and Social Welfare in the Philippines.]]\nThe '''Jose Fabella Memorial School''' ([[Filipino language|Filipino]]: ''Pang-alaalang Paaralang Jose Fabella''; abbreviated as '''JFMS''' and commonly known as '''Fabella''') is a [[Public education|public]] integrated [[special school]] located in Welfareville Compound, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]] in [[Metro Manila]],  [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/|title=About Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Founded on December 3, 1925 as the Welfareville School, it is considered as one of the oldest [[School|educational institutions]] in [[Mandaluyong City]] and is currently one of the four public [[Special education|special schools]] in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncda.gov.ph/list-of-sped-centers/government-special-schools/|title=Government Special Schools|last=|first=|date=2019|website=National Council on Disability Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It serves as the [[umbrella organization]] of 12 [[special education]] units located in different parts of [[Metro Manila]] and [[Rizal]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/organization/|title=Organization of Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and offers [[kindergarten]], [[Primary education|elementary]], [[Secondary education|secondary]] ([[Middle school|junior]] and senior high school) and [[Special education|special educatio]]<nowiki/>n to regular [[student]]s and [[Special education|students with additional needs]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==History==\nThe history of JFMS traces its roots to Act No. 267 enacted by the [[Philippine Legislature]] on January 10, 1917 which established the first [[government]] [[orphanage]] and marked the beginning of the national child welfare program in the [[Philippines]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Pangan|first=Angela Maria|date=1999|title=Looking into the Philippine foster care experience: Trends and challenges|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/children-australia/article/div-classtitlelooking-into-the-philippine-foster-care-experience-trends-and-challengesdiv/CB173688CA6B85C580B886DFD337370D|journal=Children Australia|volume=24|issue=4|pages=76\u201388|doi=10.1017/S1035077200009421|issn=1035-0772|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Bunye|first=Alfredo M.|date=January\u2013March 1958|title=The Philippine Prison System|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=yKsiAQAAIAAJ&dq|journal=Unitas|volume=31|issue=1|pages=121\u2013169|via=}}</ref> On December 3, 1924, Act No. 3203 was passed placing \"public institutions intended for the care, custody, correction, education and training of [[orphan]]s, homeless, neglected, [[Child abuse|abused]], defective and [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquent]] children under the administration and supervision of the Bureau of Public Welfare\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Murillo|first=Agapita|date=1944|title=Public Welfare Services in the Philippines, 1898-1941|journal=Social Service Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=189\u2013204|jstor=30014210|doi=10.1086/634860}}</ref> On January 6, 1925, the Bureau of Public Welfare purchased a 56-hectare land in the municipality of [[Mandaluyong|San Felipe Neri]], [[Rizal|Province of Rizal]], where the [[government]]'s child-caring institutions were established on December 3, 1925 and collectively called Welfareville Institutions.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Glimpses of What Was Welfareville \"The Children's Village\" by Recollection|last=Ramos|first=Ike|date=June 1988|work=The Welfarevillians|access-date=|volume=1|page=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zrvvwQEACAAJ|title=Annual Report of the Governor General of the Philippine Islands, 1925|last=|first=|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1927|isbn=|location=Washington|pages=76}}</ref> It originally consisted of 1) the Philippine Training School for Boys and the Philippine Training School for Girls, which catered to [[Juvenile delinquency|delinquent]] boys and girls; 2) [[orphanage]], to provide for the care of destitute children and children of [[Leprosy|leprous]] parents; 3) nursery for non-leprous children below two years of age, to provide care of children of [[Leprosy|leprous]] parents born in [[Culion leper colony|Culion]];<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arcilla|first=Jose S.|date=2009|title=The Culion Leper Colony, 1900s-1970s|journal=Philippine Studies|volume=57|issue=2|pages=307\u2013326|jstor=42634012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.dukeupress.edu/colonial-pathologies|title=Colonial Pathologies: American Tropical Medicine, Race, and Hygiene in the Philippines|last=Anderson|first=Warwick|date=2006|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0822388081|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> 4) home for the [[Intellectual disability|mentally-defective]] children, to provide care and treatment of boys and girls who are [[Intellectual disability|mentally defective]]; and 5) home for the aged and the infirm, to provide [[Nursing home care|institutional care]] for such persons who are [[Extreme poverty|destitute]].<ref name=\":3\" /> A school was also established, called Welfareville School, to provide [[Education|academic instruction and vocational training]] to [[orphan]]s and wards of Welfareville Institutions.\n\nDue to the increasing number of [[orphan]]s and other beneficiaries admitted to Welfareville Institutions, a sum of \u20b160,000 was appropriated by the end of 1929 for the construction of additional buildings for [[orphan]]s, [[Cripple|invalids]], and aged people.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=9gErAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Public Laws Enacted by the Philippine Legislature during the Period August 9, 1929 to February 7, 1930|last=|first=|publisher=Bureau of Printing|year=1930|isbn=|volume=25|location=Manila, Philippines|pages=522}}</ref> A sum of \u20b121,000 was also appropriated by virtue of Commonwealth Act No. 61 enacted on October 20, 1936 for the continued operation and maintenance of Welfareville Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1936/10/20/commonwealth-act-no-61/|title=Commonwealth Act No. 61|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1936|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn December 11, 1958, President [[Carlos P. Garcia]] issued Executive Order No. 326 reorganizing the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] (an agency created following the abolition of Bureau of Public Welfare) which used to administer and supervise the Welfareville Institutions. This resulted to the transfer of oversight of Welfareville School to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]]. Under this arrangement, the Welfareville School provided [[Education|formal education]] to [[orphan]]s and wards of Welfareville Institutions which it subsequently called \"[[special education]] units,<nowiki>''</nowiki> with the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] retaining jurisdiction of the institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1958/12/11/executive-order-no-326-s-1958/|title=Executive Order No. 326, s. 1958|last=|first=|date=December 11, 1958|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\nFor many years since its establishment, there have been calls to change the name of the school to remove the [[Social stigma|stigma]] associated with it as the \"dumping ground of society's rejects.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://jfmsmandaluyong.wordpress.com/about/history/|title=History of Jose Fabella Memorial School|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Jose Fabella Memorial School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1969/01/27/ferdinand-e-marcos-fourth-state-of-the-nation-address-january-27-1969/|title=President Ferdinand Marcos' Fourth State of the Nation Address|last=|first=|date=January 7, 1969|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On June 21, 1963, Republic Act No. 3576 was passed changing the name of Welfareville School to Jose Fabella Memorial School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra1963/ra_3576_1963.html|title=Republic Act No. 3576|last=|first=|date=2019|website=The LawPhil Project of Arellano Law Foundation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/republic-acts/ra-no-3576.php|title=Republic Act No 3576|last=|first=|date=2019|website=The Corporis Juris|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This was in honor of Dr. [[Jos\u00e9 Fabella|Jose Fabella]], the first Commissioner of the Bureau of Public Welfare<ref name=\":3\" /> and considered as the Father of Public Health and Social Welfare in the Philippines,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oqIMAQAAMAAJ|title=White Hero: Dr. Jose F. Fabella, 1888-1945, Father of Public Health and Social Welfare|last=Ricafrente|first=Gerardo S.|publisher=Richforehead Publications|year=2008|isbn=9789719236443|location=Mandaluyong City, Philippines|pages=}}</ref> who laid the plan for the development of Welfareville Institutions.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/node/1659|title=Dr. Jose F. Fabella|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an agreement between the [[Philippine]] [[government]] and the [[United Nations Children's Fund]] to upgrade the child welfare services in the Philippines, Republic Act No. 5260 was enacted on June 15, 1968 which called for the [[Decentralization|dispersion]] and [[decentralization]] of the Welfareville Institutions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chanrobles.com/republicacts/republicactno5260.html|title=Republic Act No. 5260|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Chan Robles Virtual Law Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This led to the dispersal of the [[special education]] units of JFMS in [[Metro Manila]] and outskirts. On August 11, 2011, Republic Act No. 9155 was passed which placed JFMS under the Schools Division Office of [[Mandaluyong City]].\n\nAt present, JFMS is one of the four public [[Special education|special schools]] in the [[Philippines]]<ref name=\":1\" /> and consists of a flagship [[campus]] in [[Mandaluyong City]] which caters to regular students and students with learning disabilities and behavioral problems and 12 [[special education]] units located in different parts of [[Metro Manila]] and [[Rizal]] which cater to students with [[Special education|additional needs]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n===    JFMS Units ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Unit\n!Location\n!Learners' Profile\n|-\n|Nayon ng Kabataan\n|Welfareville Compound, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|[[Child abuse|abused]], [[Orphan|orphaned]], [[Child abandonment|abandoned]], [[Child neglect|neglected]] and [[Child sexual abuse|exploited]] children aged 7 to 17 years old\n|-\n|Bagong Sinag Special School\n|[[National Center for Mental Health]], [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|[[Intellectual disability|mentally-handicapped]] patients\n|-\n|Jose Fabella Center\n|Correctional Road, [[Mandaluyong|Mandaluyong City]]\n|strandees, [[Homelessness|transients]], [[Vagrancy|vagrants]] and [[Mendicant|mendicants]]\n|-\n|[[Dangerous Drugs Board]]\u2014[[European Union]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Center\n|[[Diliman, Quezon City]]\n|people with [[Substance dependence|drug dependence]]\n|-\n|CRIBS Foundation, Inc.\n|Industrial Valley, [[Marikina|Marikina City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]], [[Child neglect|neglected]], surrendered and female minor survivors of [[child abuse]]\n|-\n|Special Learning Center\n|City Hall, [[Quezon City]]\n|children with [[Juvenile delinquency|behavioral problems]]\n|-\n|[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] Treatment and Rehabilitation Center\n|Bicutan, [[Taguig|Taguig City]]\n|children and adults with [[Addiction|drug addiction]]\n|-\n|Elsie Gaches Village\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]] and [[Child neglect|neglected]] children with mild to severe [[Intellectual disability|mental disorders]]\n|-\n|National Training School for Girls\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|[[Child abandonment|abandoned]] female street children\n|-\n|National Training School for Boys\n|[[Tanay, Rizal]]\n|[[Juvenile delinquency|male juveniles]] in conflict with the law aged 9 to 17 years old\n|-\n|Haven for Children\n|[[Alabang]], [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]]\n|boys aged 7 to 13 recovering from [[substance abuse]]\n|-\n|Molave Youth Homes\n|[[Quezon City|Diliman, Quezon City]]\n|children with [[Juvenile delinquency|behavioral problems]]\n|}\n\n==Administration==\n{| style=\"float:right; margin:1em; width:18em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; padding:2px; bg-color=yellow; text-align:right;\"\n|- style=\"background:#026f27; text-align:center;\"\n|<span style=\"color:white;\">'''School Principals of <br />Jose Fabella Memorial School'''</span>\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Maximo C. Songco'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Ignacio F. Lim'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Ignacio N. Alcantara'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Gerardo A. Consolacion'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Fortunata A. Rabang'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Aida S. Damian*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Alicia B. Reyes*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Arsenia C. Lara*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Erdelinda G. Diaz*'''\n|- style=\"text-align:left; font-size:x-small;\"\n|'''Olivia L. Pagurayan'''\n----<nowiki>*</nowiki>''---served as Officer-in-Charge of the Office of the Principal''\n|}\n\nSince its establishment as Welfareville School on December 3, 1925, the [[school]] was governed by Bureau of Public Welfare under the Department of Public Instruction from 1925 to 1938 and under the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health and Public Welfare]] from 1939 to 1946. On October 4, 1947, the administration and supervision of Welfareville School was transferred to the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Commission]] which replaced the Bureau of Public Welfare after its abolition.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=http://digitallibrary.usc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p15799coll39/id/232620/rec/1|title=The Philippines' Social Welfare Administration: A Historical Account of its Formation, 1946-1956.|last=de Guzman|first=Leonora|publisher=Master's Thesis, University of Southern California|date=January 1964|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> On January 3, 1951, President [[Elpidio Quirino]] issued Executive Order No. 396 converting the Social Welfare Commission into [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1951/01/03/executive-order-no-396-s-1951/|title=Executive Order No. 396, s. 1951|last=|first=|date=January 3, 1951|website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, thereby making it the governing agency of Welfareville School. Following the reorganization of the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development|Social Welfare Administration]] on December 11, 1958, the oversight of Welfareville School was transferred to the Special Subjects and Services Division, and later to the Special Education Unit of the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]].<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nAt present, JFMS is directly supervised by the Schools Division Office of [[Mandaluyong City]] which oversees all public and private elementary and secondary [[School|educational institutions]], including [[Alternative Learning System (Philippines)|alternative learning systems]] in its jurisdiction.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://depedmandaluyong.org/schools/|title=Schools of DepEd Mandaluyong|last=|first=|date=2019|website=DepEd Mandaluyong|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> JFMS is headed by a [[Special education|Special Education]] [[Principal (education)|Principal]] with the assistance of three Assistant [[Principal (education)|Principals]], for [[Primary school|Grade School]], [[Middle school|Junior High School]], and [[Secondary school|Senior High School]], all of whom are designated by the Schools Division Office. The [[special education]] units of JFMS are headed by Teachers-in-Charge designated by the [[Principal (education)|principal]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nJFMS is broadly organized into three [[Academic department|departments]]: [[Primary school|Grade School]], [[Middle school|Junior High School]], and [[Secondary school|Senior High School]], each headed by a [[Academic department|department]] head; 12 grade levels: Grades 1 to 12, each headed by a grade level chairperson; and eight subject areas for [[Primary school|Grade School]] and [[Middle school|Junior High School]], each headed by a subject area coordinator.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAs of 2015, JFMS had a total of 104 personnel complement, including 39 elementary and 36 secondary [[special education]] [[teacher]]s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Campus==\nThe main [[campus]] of JFMS sits on a portion of 56-hectare [[government]] land which is now the sprawling Welfareville Compound.<ref name=\":5\" /> Other [[Government agency|government agencies]] located along the vicinity of JFMS include the Nayon ng Kabataan (front), Welfareville Commission (left) and Commission on Population (right). The units of JFMS are located in [[Metro Manila]], except for the National Training School for Boys which is situated in [[Tanay, Rizal]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==People==\nPeople affiliated with JFMS as [[student]]s, [[Alumnus|graduates]], and [[Teacher|teaching]] and non-teaching personnel are called \"Fabellans.\" [[Alumnus|Graduates]] of the school are inducted annually as members of the Jose Fabella Memorial School Alumni Association. Olivia L. Pagurayan, a former [[professor]] of [[special education]] at [[Philippine Normal University]], serves as its current [[principal (education)|principal]].\n\n===    Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc. ===\nFounded in 1955 as Orphans' Association, the Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc. is a non-stock and [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organization]] of former [[orphan]]s, wards, and employees of Welfareville Institutions and [[Alumnus|graduates]] of Welfareville School.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Welfarevillians Foundation, Inc.|last=|first=|date=June 1988|work=The Welfarevillians|access-date=|volume=1|page=1}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Jfms bust.jpg|Bust of Dr. Jose Fabella\nFile:Main quadrangle.jpg|JFMS quadrangle facing the administration building\nFile:High school building.jpg|One of the high school buildings\nFile:JFMS SPED Building.jpg|Special education building \nFile:JFMS-NTSG.jpg|Signage of JFMS at National Training School for Girls in Alabang, Muntinlupa City\nFile:Haven for Children.jpg|JFMS building at Haven for Children in Alabang, Muntinlupa City \nFile:JFMS 1960.jpg|Former Gabaldon building, ca. 1980s\nFile:Jfms tower.jpg|Former dormitory of Philippine Training School for Boys, ca. 1960s\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{portal|Philippines|Schools}}\n\n[[Category:Special schools in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Schools in Mandaluyong]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1925]]\n", "name_user": "Motmoterz 23", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added logo in compliance with copyright.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jose_Fabella_Memorial_School"}
{"title_page": "List of Old Bedford Modernians", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n[[File:Harpur Window.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The Harpur Window, [[Bedford Modern School]]. ''They Shall Mount Up With Wings As Eagles'']]\n\nThe following is a list of some notable '''Old Bedford Modernians''' who are former pupils of [[Bedford Modern School]] in [[Bedford]], England.  At the school, alumni are known as '''OBMs'''.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bedmod.co.uk/obms/|title=OBMs|website=Bedford Modern School}}</ref>  The Old Bedford Modernians' Club was founded in 1892.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n==Academic and educational==\n[[File:William A. Tilden by Harry H. Salomon.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[William A. Tilden|Sir William Tilden FRS]]]]\n[[File:John Holland Rose.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[John Holland Rose|Prof. John Holland Rose FBA]]]]\n[[File:Sir Peter Knight and Dr Andrew Miller (7985176466).jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[Peter Knight (scientist)|Sir Peter Knight FRS]]]]\n[[File:Peter Wothers portrait by Nathan Pitt.jpg|thumb|115px|right|[[Peter Wothers|Dr. Peter Wothers MBE]]]]\n* [[William Augustus Tilden|Sir William Augustus Tilden]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1842\u20131926), Chemist & Dean, [[Royal College of Science]], London<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\">{{Cite book|title=Bedford Modern School of the black & red|work=worldcat.org|isbn=9780950760803|year=1981|oclc = 16558393}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Reynolds Green|Professor Joseph Reynolds Green]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1848\u20131914), Professor of Botany to the [[Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain]]<ref>''The Eagle'', The Magazine of [[Bedford Modern School]], Vol. III (1888), p. 243</ref><ref>''The Eagle'' Vol. XXVII, no. 2 (1949), p. 135</ref>\n* [[William Hillhouse|Professor William Hillhouse]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (1850\u20131910), first Professor of Botany at the [[University of Birmingham]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Edward Mann Langley]] (1851\u20131933), founded the [[Mathematical Gazette]], created [[Langley\u2019s Adventitious Angles]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[William Robert Bousfield]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (1854\u20131943), [[Physical chemistry|chemist]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[John Holland Rose|Professor John Holland Rose]] [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (1855\u20131942), [[Vere Harmsworth Professor of Imperial and Naval History]], [[University of Cambridge]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[George Charles Crick]] [[Geological Society of London|FGS]] [[Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] (1856\u20131917), geologist, authority on [[Cephalopod]]a, 1st Assistant at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/library/archives/catalogue/dserve.exe?dsqServer=placid&dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Persons&dsqSearch=Code==%27PX174%27&dsqCmd=Show.tcl|title=Natural History Museum Archive Catalogue|work=nhm.ac.uk|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Arthur John Pressland]] [[Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] (1865 \u20131934), educational theorist, linguist, schoolmaster and writer<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Harpur Trust, 1552-1973.|publisher=|isbn=9780950291703|year=1973|oclc = 903515}}</ref>\n* [[George James Gibbs]] [[Royal Astronomical Society|FRAS]] (1866\u20131947), astronomer, engineer, inventor and public science lecturer<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/mnras/109.1.1 |title=Meeting of 1949 January 14 |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=109 |pages=1\u20132 |year=1949 |last1=Greaves |first1=W. M. H. }}</ref>\n* [[Richard John Durley|Professor Richard John Durley]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (1868\u20131948), Professor of Mechanical Engineering at [[McGill University]] (1901\u201312)<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1680/IJOTI.1948.13374 |title=Obituary. Richard John Durley, 1868-1948 |journal=Journal of the Institution of Civil Engineers |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=183 |year=1948 }}</ref>\n* [[Laxton Brothers|Edward Augustine Lowe Laxton]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (1869\u20131951), expert on fruit production (''[[Laxton's Superb]]'')<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Professor Henry Payne]] [[Royal Aeronautical Society|FRAeS]] [[Institution of Civil Engineers|M.Inst.C.E.]] (1871\u20131945), Professor of Engineering at the [[University of Melbourne]]<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/payne-henry-7989|title=Biography \u2013 Henry Payne \u2013 Australian Dictionary of Biography|work=anu.edu.au|accessdate=29 January 2015|chapter=Payne, Henry (1871\u20131945)|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University}}</ref>\n* [[Jannion Steele Elliott]] (1871\u20131942), [[ornithology|ornithologist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishbirds.co.uk/article/obituary-jannion-steele-elliott-1871-1942/|title=Obituary: Jannion Steele Elliott (1871\u20131942)|work=British Birds|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Eric Temple Bell|Dr Eric Temple Bell]], (1883\u20131960), mathematician who specialised in [[number theory]] and formulated the [[Bell series]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aoctKmbvtMYC&pg=PA354&lpg=PA354&dq=edward+mann+langley+alumni#v=onepage&q=edward%20mann%20langley%20alumni|title=The Search for E. T. Bell|accessdate=29 January 2015|isbn=9780883855089|year=1993|last1=Reid|first1=Constance}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Oatley|Sir Charles Oatley]] [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[Royal Society|FRS]] [[FREng]] (1904\u20131996), pioneered the development of the [[scanning electron microscope]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-professor-sir-charles-oatley-1343206.html|title=Obituary: Professor Sir Charles Oatley|work=The Independent|accessdate=29 January 2015|date=1996-03-21}}</ref>\n* [[Gerald Dunning|Dr. G.C. Dunning]], [[Doctor of Letters|D.Lit]], [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (1905\u20131978), pioneering medieval archaeologist, authority on Anglo-Saxon and medieval ceramics<ref>Obituary in ''[[The Times]]'', ''Dr. G.C. Dunning'', ''Work on Medieval Pottery'', 28 April 1978, p.18</ref><ref>A.Underwood, ''School of the Black and Red. A history of Bedford Modern School'' (Bedford, 2010 edn.), p. 130</ref>\n* [[William Francis Grimes|Professor William Francis Grimes]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1905\u20131988), Professor of Archaeology, [[University of London]] (1956\u20131973)<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[Francis MacCarthy Willis Bund|Reverend Francis MacCarthy Willis Bund]] (1906\u20131980), Chaplain, [[Dean (education)|Dean]] and [[Fellow]] of [[Balliol College, Oxford]]<ref>A. Underwood ''The School of the Black and Red''(Bedord, 2010 edn.) p. 284</ref>\n* [[D. C. Riddy|Dr D. C. Riddy]] [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (1907\u20131979), Controller-General of the Education Branch, [[Allied Commission|Control Commission for German \u2013 British Element]]<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/>\n* [[F.G. Emmison]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] [[Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] [[Historical Society|FRHistS]] (1907\u20131995), archivist, author and historian<ref name=\"Underwood 1981\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/60/101060381/|title=Frederick Emmison|work=oxforddnb.com|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n* [[J.P.C. Roach|Professor John Roach]] (1920 \u2013 2015), historian<ref name=\"google.co.uk\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eNo9AAAAYAAJ&dq=educated+bedford+modern+school+new+college+oxford&q=Bedford|title=Essays to a young teacher|year=1966|last1=Howat|first1=Gerald Malcolm David}}</ref>\n* [[Ramsay Shearman|Professor Ramsay Shearman]] DSc [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FReng]] [[Fellow of the Institution of Engineering and Technology|FIET]] [[Royal Meteorological Society|FRMetS]] [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|FIEEE]] (1924-2019), pioneer in shortwave radio and radar<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ramsay-shearman-obituary-98llh6w0j|title=Ramsay Shearman obituary|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Brian Gl\u00fcss|Professor Brian Gl\u00fcss]] [[Royal Statistical Society|FRSS]] (1930\u20132013), statistician, mathematician, systems engineer, author and expert on [[survivor guilt]]<ref>Obituary, ''Dr Brian Gl\u00fcss'', ''Eagle News'', The Magazine of the [[Bedford Modern School|Old Bedford Modernians' Club]], New Series, Volume 6, Number 3 (Issue 110), January 2015</ref>\n* [[John Richard Anthony Pearson|Professor John Richard Anthony Pearson]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] [[Institute of Materials, Minerals and Mining|FIMMM]] [[Institution of Chemical Engineers|MIChemE]] (born 1930), pioneer in [[fluid mechanics]]<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/whos-who-and-who-was-who-9780199540891?cc=mt&lang=en&|title=Who's Who and Who Was Who: For autobiographical information on the noteworthy & famous.|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Oxford University Press}}</ref>\n* [[D.J. Bartholomew|Professor David John Bartholomew]] [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] (1931-2017), Professor of Statistics at the [[London School of Economics|LSE]] (1973\u201396)<ref name=\"Underwood 2010\">''School of the Black And Red'' by Andrew Underwood 1981. Reset and updated by Peter Boon, Paul Middleton and Richard Wildman in 2010</ref>\n* [[Philip Bean|Professor Philip Bean]] (born 1936), Professor of [[Criminology]] at [[Loughborough University]], former President of the [[British Society of Criminology|British Soc. of Criminology]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n* [[George Richard Pickett|Professor George Richard Pickett]] [[Royal Society|FRS]] (born 1939), Professor of [[Cryogenics|Low Temperature Physics]] at [[Lancaster University]]<ref name=\"Underwood 2010\"/>\n* [[Sid Gray|Professor Sid Gray]] PhD [[FASSA]] [[Chartered Certified Accountan